{
  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustic devices to reduce human-wildlife conflict at aquaculture systems compare to their use on fishing gear?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for acoustic devices to reduce human-wildlife conflict differs substantially between aquaculture systems and fishing gear contexts. At aquaculture systems (action 2775), six studies were evaluated, with four of six studies finding that acoustic devices reduced predation on caged salmon by grey seals, harbour seals and South American sea lions, or reduced the number of harbour seals approaching fish cages. However, two studies found that acoustic devices did not reduce harbour seal predation at salmon farms or reduce the presence, approach distances, group sizes or time spent around fin-fish farms by common bottlenose dolphins.\n\nFor fishing gear (action 2808), thirty-three studies were evaluated, showing much more extensive evidence. In terms of human-wildlife conflict specifically, five of six controlled studies found that acoustic devices reduced damage to fish catches and/or fishing nets caused by common bottlenose dolphins and seals, while one study found acoustic devices did not reduce damage to swordfish catches by California sea lions. Additionally, fishing gear studies demonstrated significant evidence for reducing entanglements, with nine studies finding that acoustic devices resulted in fewer collisions of humpback whales or entanglements of harbour porpoises, Franciscana dolphins, beaked whales and small cetaceans.\n\nThe fishing gear evidence base is substantially larger (33 vs 6 studies) and shows broader applications across more marine mammal species and geographical locations. Acoustic devices on fishing gear also demonstrated effectiveness for both reducing unwanted catch/entanglements (14 studies) and human-wildlife conflict (6 studies), while aquaculture studies focused primarily on predation reduction at fish farms.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2775",
    "2808"
  ]
}

