tools_called.args:
{"query": "How do the outcomes of using catch protection devices on longlines compare to modifying fishing pots for reducing human-wildlife conflict?", "summary": "Catch protection devices on longlines showed mixed effectiveness in reducing human-wildlife conflict. Two of four studies found that net sleeves or cage and chain devices on fishing hooks reduced damage to fish catches by sperm whales, killer whales and toothed whales (Action 2821). However, two other studies found that attaching 'umbrella' or 'spider' devices on fishing hooks did not reduce predation and/or damage to fish catches by sperm whales or toothed whales (Action 2821). One study found that catch protection devices made from streamers reduced dolphin predation on fish bait, but only during the first two trials (Action 2821).

In contrast, modifying fishing pots and traps showed more consistent positive outcomes for reducing human-wildlife conflict. Two controlled studies found that installing wire grids or steel bars on fishing trap-nets or bag-nets, along with strengthened netting or other modifications to prevent seal access, reduced damage to salmon catches by seals (Action 2822). One study found that one of two methods of securing crab pot doors with a bungee cord reduced common bottlenose dolphin interactions (Action 2822). One study found that installing wire grids on trap-nets, along with strengthened netting, resulted in higher catches of undamaged salmon but not whitefish, likely due to reduced seal predation (Action 2822).

Both approaches also showed effectiveness in reducing entanglements and unwanted catch. Catch protection devices resulted in fewer unwanted catches of toothed whales (Action 2821), while modified fishing pots reduced the number of Australian sea lion pups or grey seals and harbour seals that entered or became trapped in pots (Action 2822).", "action_ids": ["2821","2822"]}

