{
  "query": "What are the documented behavioral effects on marine mammals of implementing regulations for vessel operations during tourism activities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the documented evidence, four studies have evaluated the behavioral effects of implementing regulations for marine and freshwater mammal watching tours. These studies were conducted in the North Atlantic Ocean (the Azores), the Canan\u00e9ia estuary (Brazil), the South Pacific Ocean (Australia) and the Bass Strait (Australia). Two controlled studies in the North Atlantic Ocean and South Pacific Ocean found that when whale-watching vessels followed approach regulations, fewer sperm whales and humpback whale pods changed their behaviours (e.g. swimming speed, aerial displays) or avoided the vessels compared to when regulations were not followed, but direction of movement and diving patterns or diving behaviours did not differ. One replicated, controlled study in the Canan\u00e9ia estuary found that when tour boats followed approach regulations, fewer Guiana dolphins displayed negative behaviours (e.g. moving away, diving, groups separating). One study in the Bass Strait found that when boats approached a seal colony to 75 m, more seals remained on shore than when boats approached to 25 m. Additionally, one before-and-after study in the Kenai Fjords (Alaska) found that fewer harbour seals were disturbed during kayak excursions after training was provided to kayak guides. No studies were found that evaluated the effects of developing and implementing regulations for operating vessels around mammals generally, introducing permits or licences for marine and freshwater mammal watching tours, providing training to vessel operators on mammal behaviour and appropriate avoidance techniques, or setting minimum distances for approaching mammals.",
