{"query": "For shark control programs in Australia and South Africa, what is the evidence for alternative methods to nets that reduce harm to marine mammals?", "summary": "The evidence for alternative methods to nets in shark control programs comes primarily from studies evaluating baited lines as an alternative to nets. Two studies from the Indian Ocean (South Africa) and South Pacific Ocean (Australia) found that using baited lines instead of nets for shark control had fewer entanglements of dolphins, whales and dugongs than nets (Action 2856). Additionally, one site comparison study in the South Pacific Ocean found that using baited lines instead of nets increased the survival of entangled common and bottlenose dolphins (Action 2856). 

For reducing harm from fishing nets more generally, several methods show promise: Installing exclusion and/or escape devices on fishing nets reduced the number of trapped or entangled Antarctic fur seals and common bottlenose dolphins in studies from the South Atlantic Ocean and Indian Ocean (Action 2823). However, less than one third of common bottlenose dolphins exited escape hatches on trawl nets alive in one Indian Ocean study (Action 2823). 

Acoustic devices on fishing gear showed mixed results across multiple locations including Australia. Nine studies found that using acoustic devices on cod traps or fishing nets resulted in fewer collisions of humpback whales or entanglements of harbour porpoises, Franciscana dolphins, beaked whales and small cetaceans (Action 2808). However, three studies found that acoustic devices resulted in fewer entanglements of some species but not others, and one study in Australia found no significant effect on the behaviour of common bottlenose dolphins, harbour porpoises, Indo-Pacific humpback dolphins or dugongs (Action 2808).", "action_ids": ["2856","2823","2808"]}

