{"query": "What actions are available to reduce the risk of lethal vessel collisions with large whales?", "summary": "Multiple actions are available to reduce the risk of lethal vessel collisions with large whales. Setting and enforcing vessel speed limits has demonstrated effectiveness, with studies showing that setting vessel speed limits during specific periods in key habitats resulted in fewer North Atlantic right whale deaths caused by collisions (Action 2777). Speed limit enforcement in all areas also showed fewer manatee deaths compared to partial enforcement in zones only (Action 2777).

Other available actions include diverting shipping routes to avoid whale habitats (Action 2754), using observers on board vessels to detect mammals and allow vessel course or speed to be altered (Action 2755), and training vessel operators on appropriate avoidance techniques to reduce collisions (Action 3534). Technology-based solutions are also available, such as using real-time automated tools on board vessels to detect mammals and allow vessel course or speed to be altered (Action 2756), using remote tools to detect mammals in an area and allow vessel course or speed to be altered (Action 2757), and using technology and reporting systems to avoid collisions (Action 3535).

Additional vessel modifications include modifying vessels to reduce risk of physical injury to mammals (Action 2762) and reducing shipping along inland waterways (Action 2763). However, for most of these actions except speed limits, no studies have yet been found that directly evaluated their effectiveness on marine mammal populations.", "action_ids": ["2754","2777","2755","3534","2756","2762","2757","2763","3535"]}

